@endnode


@node why "   How Pict2Source was born"

              @{u}How @{b}Pict2Source@{ub} was born.@{uu}


   @{b}Pict2Source@{ub} is a program born for my personal use, allowing me to convert
   IFF pictures to C sources for my programs. I have looked for some time
   a program that do this function but i found only "MakeC" on CDPDI ,a good program 
   but very old for the new Amiga family. So i decide to build by myself the program. I
   decide to use only 3.0 features because the new O.S. offers more facilities for
   the Lazy Programmers, and i'm a VERY Lazy Programmer! Special Thanks to my
   friend Georg Campana a computer-guy that have incited me to work on this
   program for many weeks ,without Georg the program could never be born. With Georg
   we have build a fantastic routine that defring @{"HAM"link ham} very well! With
   this routine you can clip your ham pieces and enjoy a fantastic HAM user
   interface (if you have patience to build them!).


@endnode

@node ham "   Pict2Source and the HAM mode"

              @{u}@{b}Pict2Source@{ub} and the HAM mode@{uu}


       @{b}Pict2Source@{ub} can handle also HAM8 and HAM6 graphics files ,and allows
       the cut of the image. Don't worry if you have some beautifuls "frings" at
       the moment of clipping, because the program "defringing" your clip before you
       save it. The defringing routine have a sufficent speed, but could be modifiable
       to get a better speed.If you have cut a big clip of your image probably
       you will wait some time necessary to defringing the clip.
       Boyz, HAM is like AIDS if you know it, it don't kill you....
       (from a famous italian spot about AIDS).

@endnode
        
@node what " What is Pict2Source"

             @{u}What is @{b}Pict2Source@{ub}@{uu}


    @{b}Pict2Source@{ub} is a program that converts graphics files to C sources
    that you can include in your program.
    The features of the program are:

    ° The Program is @{fg fill}3.0+ ONLY !!@{fg text}
    
    ° The program uses DataTypes availables starting with the Version 3.0 of the O.S,
      to load pictures in memory and show them, so if you have new datatypes
      you can load new graphics formats.

    ° It's possible to save a @{fg fill}BitMap@{fg text} @{"structure"link struct}
      or a @{fg fill}Image@{fg text} structure .
    
    ° It's possible to define from the program if the resultant saved structure must be
      in @{fg fill} CHIP@{fg text} or in@{fg fill} PUBLIC@{fg text} @{"memory"link mem}.
    
    ° It's also possible to save from the program a @{"ColorTable" link cmap} of the
      loaded picture to use it with LoadRGB32 or LoadRGB4.

    ° The program can also clipping the showed picture,and save the clip.

    ° The program always save as #defines :
      The @{fg fill}MODE ID@{fg text} to use with OpenScreen.
      The @{fg fill}OFFSETX@{fg text} x offset of the Clip.
      The @{fg fill}OFFSETY@{fg text} y offset of the Clip.
      The @{fg fill}DIMENSX@{fg text} x dimension of the Clip.
      The @{fg fill}DIMENSY@{fg text} y dimension of the Clip.
    
@endnode

@node start "   How to use Pict2Source "


                @{u}How to use @{b}Pict2Source@{ub}@{uu}




    @{b}Pict2Source@{ub} was born to run under O.S 3.0

    It's possible to run @{b}Pict2Source@{ub} from @{"CLI" link CLI} or Shell like any
    other command , or from @{"WorkBench" link WB} with his GUI wich allows to work on
    the picture. If you start from the Workbench, the tooltypes of the program icon
    will be used as default parameters. You can depth arrange the GUI with the picture using
    the right mouse button. Click on picture to cut a part of them, and to the
    info button to get some infos about picture or about the clipped part. If you
    click on rmb when you are in clipping mode you abort the previous drawed cross
    on the picture. Press the @{fg back}@{bg text}SAVE@{fg text}@{bg back} Gadget
    to choose the file header (where and what is the name if you won't default) end
    with the String Gadget you can define the @{"basename" link bname} of the
    structure.

@endnode

@node CLI " Use Pict2Source as CLI command"

            @{u}Use @{b}Pict2Source@{ub} as CLI command@{uu}


     Is  possible to use @{b}Pict2Source@{ub} as a CLI command
        
       The use is:

   Pict2Source [QUIET=YES/NO] [LOADPATH=<loadfilepath>]
                              [SAVEPATH=<savefilepath>]
                              [COLORMAP=NONE/LOADRGB32/LOADRGB4]
                              [MEMTYPE=CHIP/PUBLIC]
                              [STRUCTTYPE=IMAGE/BITMAP]
                              [BASENAME= <basename>]

        
Remember that all the Keywords (ex: QUIET,MEMTYPE...) can be written in lower or
upper case ,but the parameter must have the first character in upper-case.


      @{"  QUIET       "link quiet}   --    select of quiet mode.

      @{"  LOADPATH    "link lpath}   --    graphics file to load.

      @{"  SAVEPATH    "link spath}   --    file header to save.

      @{"  COLORMAP    "link cmap}   --    ColorMap to save.

      @{"  MEMTYPE     "link mem }   --    Where to load the data ?

      @{"  STRUCTTYPE  "link struct }   --    What kind of structure to save?

      @{"  BASENAME    "link bname }   --    What's the name of the structure?
                    
@endnode

@node WB "    Use of Pict2Source from the WorkBench"

              @{u}Use of @{b}Pict2Source@{ub} from the WorkBench@{uu}


If you run @{b}Pict2Source@{ub} from WorkBench ,you have the possibility 
to change some parameters changing the icon TOOLTYPES .
Remember that all the Keywords (ex: QUIET) can be written in lower or upper-case
but the parameter must have the first character in upper-case .

      @{"  LOADDIR    "link ldir}   --    default directory for load.

      @{"  SAVEDIR    "link sdir}   --    default directory for save.

      @{"  SAVEFILE   "link sfile}   --    file header to save.

      @{"  COLORMAP    "link cmap}   --    ColorMap to save.

      @{"  MEMTYPE     "link mem }   --    Where to load the data ?

      @{"  STRUCTTYPE  "link struct }   --    What kind of structure to save?

      @{"  BASENAME    "link bname }   --    What's the name of the structure?



@endnode

@node quiet "       Select of QUIET mode"


                    @{u}Select of @{b}QUIET@{ub} mode@{uu}

    QUIET=
         YES  - Don't show the info messages when the program works .

         NO   - Show info messages about the actual state of the program.

    Omitting this parameter @{b}Pict2Source@{ub} gets as default "NO".

@endnode

@node mem "       Select of MEMTYPE"


                  @{u}Select of @{b}MEMTYPE@{ub}@{uu}

 MEMTYPE=
         CHIP   - the resultant data, when compiled, will be in CHIP memory.

         PUBLIC - the resultant data, when compiled, will be in PUBLIC memory.

    Omitting this parameter @{b}Pict2Source@{ub} gets as default "CHIP".

@endnode

@node struct "       Select of STRUCTTYPE"


                @{u}Select of @{b}STRUCTTYPE@{ub}@{uu}

 STRUCTTYPE=
         
         IMAGE  - the resultant data will be a C Image structure .
         
         BITMAP - the resultant data will be a C BitMap structure .

    Omitting this parameter @{b}Pict2Source@{ub} gets as default "IMAGE".

@endnode

@node cmap "       Select of COLORMAP"


                   @{u}Select of @{b}COLORMAP@{ub}@{uu}

 COLORMAP=
         NONE      - no ColorMap to save.
         
         LOADRGB32 - The Program save a ColorMap table in the LoadRGB32() format.
         
         LOADRGB4  - The Program save a ColorMap table in the LoadRGB4() format.
         
    If you save a LoadRGB32 table then a #define with the number
    of colors in the ColorMap is written to the file header.
    
    Omitting this parameter @{b}Pict2Source@{ub} gets as default "NONE".

@endnode

@node bname "       Select of BASENAME"


                   @{u}Select of @{b}BASENAME@{ub}@{uu}

 BASENAME=<basename> 
 
         The basename to use with the saved structures, example:
         
         BASENAME=Marzia : the saved structure will be:
         
         struct Image Marzia_image={.....};

         and also for the Bitmap:

         struct BitMap Marzia_bitmap={.....};

    Omitting this parameter @{b}Pict2Source@{ub} gets the name of the loaded
    file without extensions.

@endnode

@node ldir "       Select of LOADDIR"


                   @{u}Select of @{b}LOADDIR@{ub}@{uu}

        LOADDIR=<loadpath>

                The default path where @{b}Pict2Source@{ub} will find
                the file to be loaded.

    Omitting this parameter @{b}Pict2Source@{ub} gets as load path the current
    directory.

@endnode

@node sdir "       Select of SAVEDIR"


                   @{u}Select of @{b}SAVEDIR@{ub}@{uu}

        SAVEDIR=<savepath>

                The default path where @{b}Pict2Source@{ub} will save
                the resultant file header.

    Omitting this parameter @{b}Pict2Source@{ub} gets as default the directory
    of the last loaded image.

@endnode

@node sfile "       Select of SAVEFILE"


                   @{u}Select of @{b}SAVEFILE@{ub}@{uu}

        SAVEFILE=<filename>

                The name that @{b}Pict2Source@{ub} will use to save
                the resultant file header .
                   s
    Omitting this parameter @{b}Pict2Source@{ub} gets as name the name of the
    last loaded picture,with @{b}.h@{ub} appended .

@endnode

@node lpath "       Select of LOADPATH"


                   @{u}Select of @{b}LOADPATH@{ub}@{uu}

        LOADPATH=<loadpath>

                The name of the picture to load with complete path.
    
    Omitting this parameter @{b}Pict2Source@{ub} doesn't start.

@endnode

@node spath "       Select of SAVEPATH"


                   @{u}Select of@{b}SAVEPATH@{ub}@{uu}

        SAVEPATH=<savepath>

                The name (with/out complete path) to use for the 
                generated header file .
    
    Omitting this parameter @{b}Pict2Source@{ub} will save a file
    in the same directory from where the picture was loaded.
    The name of the resultant file is the same of the picture with @{b}.h@{ub}
    appended .

@endnode

